    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.7-9_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>January 9, 1959</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Department of English</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have been watching your Telecourse series, Epic America, this week and regret that probably I have missed much that has been given previously. Being a farmer, often it isn't possible to have work done in time. The story is especially interesting to me, as my father and his brother homesteaded near Rapid City about 188<unclear>4</unclear>, and I was born in that area in 1892. We moved back to Iowa when I was a small boy, but the history of that country always interested me. Your poem is beautiful and follows closely the story as told in an old book <add>(about 700 pages)</add> I have which belonged to my father, "The Black Hills on or The Last Hunting Grounds of the Dakotahs" by <hi rend="caps">A. E.</hi> Tallent. I should be very happy to loan it to you if you haven't read it and would care to. A son of ours in school at the University can bring it over if you
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.7-9_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">8</fw>
                    
                    are interested.</p>
                
                <p>I want to thank you for the epic poem we have been privileged to hear you read. We have enjoyed it very much.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Sam R. Griffith</signed>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Route 2</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Paris, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
